[{"id":"VR876935","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">What is the distance between the sphere’s centers?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR876935_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two nonconducting spheres have different radii <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"R\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mi>R</mi> </math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction R over 2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"the fraction R over 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></span></span>, but the same mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"M\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span> and the same uniform charge density <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"rho\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"rho\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>ρ</mi></math></span></span>. The sphere of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction R over 2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"the fraction R over 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></span></span> is directly above but not touching the larger sphere, and its weight is balanced by the electrostatic force exerted by the larger sphere.</p>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"rho R squared times the square root of the fraction with numerator pi, and denominator epsilon sub 0, end sub, times M g\"><math alttext=\"rho R squared times the square root of the fraction with numerator pi, and denominator epsilon sub 0, end sub, times M g\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>ρ</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msqrt><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mrow><msub><mi>ε</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>M</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></span></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"4 rho R squa